Gamelan mln the traditional ensemble music Java and Bali Indonesia made predominantly percussive instruments The most common instruments used are metallophones played mallets and set handplayed drums called kendhang which register the beat Other instruments include xylophones bamboo flutes bowed instrument called rebab and even vocalists called sindhen Although the popularity gamelan has declined since the introduction pop music gamelan still commonly played formal occasions and many traditional Indonesian ceremonies For most Indonesians gamelan integral part Indonesian culture The word gamelan comes from the low Javanese word gamel which may refer type mallet used strike instruments the act striking with mallet The term karawitan refers classical gamelan music and performance practice and comes from the word rawit meaning intricate finely worked The word derives from the Javanese word Sanskrit origin rawit which refers the sense smoothness and elegance idealized Javanese music Another word from this root pangrawit means person with such sense and used honorific when discussing esteemed gamelan musicians The high Javanese word for gamelan gangsa formed either from the words tembaga and rejasa referring the materials used bronze gamelan construction copper and tin tiga and sedasa referring their proportions three and ten The gamelan predates the HinduBuddhist culture that dominated Indonesia its earliest records and thus represents indigenous art form contrast the heavy Indian influence other art forms the only obvious Indian influence gamelan music the Javanese style singing and the themes the Wayang kulit shadow puppet plays Javanese mythology the gamelan was created Sang Hyang Guru Saka era 167 230 the god who ruled king all Java from palace the Maendra mountain Medang Kamulan now Mount Lawu needed signal summon the gods and thus invented the gong For more complex messages invented two other gongs thus forming the original gamelan set The earliest image musical ensemble found the basrelief 8th century Buddhist monument Borobudur Central Java The Borobudurs musicians play lutelike stringed instruments kendang drums suling flutes small cymbals and bells Some these musical instruments are indeed included complete gamelan orchestra Musical instruments such the bamboo flute bells drums various sizes lute and bowed and plucked string instruments were identified this image However lacks metallophones and xylophones Nevertheless the image this musical ensemble suggested the ancient form the gamelan The instruments developed into their current form during the Majapahit Empire According the inscriptions and manuscripts dated from the Majapahit period the kingdom even had government office charge supervising the performing arts including the gamelan The arts office oversaw the construction musical instruments well scheduling performances the court the palaces Java the oldest known ensembles Gamelan Munggang and Gamelan Kodok Ngorek are apparently from the 12th century These formed the basis loud style music contrast soft style developed out the kemanak tradition and related the traditions singing Javanese poetry manner often believed similar the chorus that accompanies the modern bedhaya dance the 17th century these loud and soft styles mixed and large extent the variety modern gamelan styles Bali Java and Sunda resulted from different ways mixing these elements Thus despite the seeming diversity styles many the same theoretical concepts instruments and techniques are shared between the styles gamelan multitimbre ensemble consisting metallophones xylophones flutes gongs voices well bowed and plucked strings The handplayed drum called kendhang controls the tempo and rhythm pieces well transitions from one section another while one instrument gives melodic cues indicate treatment sections piece Some the instruments that make gamelan presentday Central Java are shown below Bonang Gendr Gong Kendang KenongKethuk Peking Saron Slenthem Varie